Algorithm 1:
A standard Newton method with block-Cholesky factorization


(0)
Compute \${\bf g}\$ and \${\bf H}\$ in Eq. (29) (e.g., see [19]) to form the Newton formula;

(1)
Perform Cholesky on the first diagonal block: \${\bf H}^{3,3}={\bf U}_{3}^{T}{\bf U}_{3}\$;
(2)
Solve a triangular system (no need to invert \${\bf U}_{3}\$): \${\bf X}={\bf H}^{2,3}{\bf U}_{3}^{-1}\$;
(3)
Solve a triangular system (without inverting \${\bf U}_{3}\$): \${\bf Y}={\bf H}^{1,3}{\bf U}_{3}^{-1}\$;
(4)
Compute a Schur complement matrix \${\bf V}_{2}\$ (using \${\bf X}\$) by: \${\bf V}_{2}={\bf H}^{2,2}-{\bf XX}^{T}\$;
(5)
Perform Cholesky on \${\bf V}_{2}={\bf U}_{2}^{T}{\bf U}_{2}\$;
(6)
Solve a triangular system (without inverting \${\bf U}_{2}\$): \${\bf Z}=[{\bf H}^{1,2}-{\bf YX}^{T}]{\bf U}_{2}^{-1}\$;
(7)
Compute a Schur complement matrix \${\bf V}_{1}\$ (using \${\bf Y}\$ and \${\bf Z})\$ by: \${\bf V}_{1}={\bf H}^{1,1}-{\bf YY}^{T}-{\bf ZZ}^{T}\$;
(8)
Perform Cholesky on \${\bf V}_{1}={\bf U}_{1}^{T}{\bf U}_{1}\$;
(9)
Solve a lower-triangular system \${\bf Lp}=-{\bf g}\$ by forward substitution;

(10)
(10) Solve an upper-triangular system \${\bf L}^{T}\delta\theta_{{\rm N}}={\bf p}\$ by back substitution.

